{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Pacem in Terris'' Award}} {{primary sources|date=January 2013}} The '''''Pacem in Terris'' Peace and Freedom Award''' is a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] peace award which has been given annually since 1964, in commemoration of the 1963 [[encyclical]] letter '' [[Pacem in terris]]'' (Peace on Earth) of [[Pope John XXIII]]. It is awarded "to honor a person for their achievements in peace and justice, not only in their country but in the world."<ref name="DD">{{cite web |title=Pacem In Terris (Peace On Earth) Award Recipients |url=http://www.davenportdiocese.org/socialaction/sapitrecipients.htm |publisher=Diocese of Davenport |accessdate=June 1, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725222132/http://www.davenportdiocese.org/socialaction/sapitrecipients.htm |archivedate=July 25, 2011 |df= }}</ref>
The award was begun in 1963 by the Davenport Catholic Interracial Council<ref name="DDintro">{{cite web |title=Pacem In Terris |url=http://www.davenportdiocese.org/socialaction/sapaceminterris.htm |publisher=Diocese of Davenport |accessdate=June 1, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512050739/http://www.davenportdiocese.org/socialaction/sapaceminterris.htm |archivedate=May 12, 2008 |df= }}</ref> of the [[Diocese of Davenport]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Iowa]]. Since 1976, the award has been presented each year by the [[Quad Cities]] Pacem in Terris Coalition. In 2010, sponsors of the award were the Diocese of Davenport, [[St. Ambrose University]], [[Augustana College (Illinois)|Augustana College]], [[Churches United]] of the Quad-Cities, [[Pax Christi]], ''The Catholic Messenger'', the [[Congregation of the Humility of Mary]], the [[Order of Saint Benedict|Sisters of St. Benedict]], the [[Islam|Muslim]] Community of the Quad Cities, and the Sisters of St. Francis.<ref name="dear">{{cite news |url=http://www.catholicmessenger.org/articles/2010/05/19/news/doc4bf40e0730eea126578341.txt |title=Peace activist Fr. John Dear to get Pacem in Terris Award |newspaper=The Catholic Messenger |location=Davenport, IA |last=Arland-Fye |first=Barb |date=May 19, 2010 |accessdate=June 1, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
Six recipients<ref>[[Martin Luther King, Jr.]], [[Mother Teresa]], [[Desmond Tutu|Archbishop Desmond Tutu]], [[Mairead Corrigan|Mairead Corrigan Maguire]], [[Adolfo Pérez Esquivel]], and [[Lech Wałęsa]]</ref> have also received a [[Nobel Peace Prize]].
==Award winners== The following are the recipients:<ref name=DD/> {{colbegin}} * 1964 [[John Howard Griffin]] and [[John F. Kennedy]] (posthumously) * 1965 Rev. [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] * 1966 [[R. Sargent Shriver]] * 1967 [[A. Philip Randolph]] * 1968 Father [[James Groppi]] * 1969 [[Saul Alinsky]] * 1972 [[Dorothy Day]], [[Servant of God|S.D.]] * 1974 Senator [[Harold Hughes]] * 1975 Dom [[Hélder Câmara]], [[Servant of God|S.D.]] * 1976 [[Mother Teresa|Saint Teresa]] of [[Calcutta]] * 1979 Bishop [[Thomas Gumbleton]] * 1980 [[Crystal Lee Sutton]] * 1980 Bishop [[Ernest Leo Unterkoefler]] * 1982 [[George F. Kennan]] * 1983 [[Helen Caldicott]] * 1985 [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]] [[Joseph Bernardin]] * 1986 Bishop [[Maurice John Dingman]] * 1987 Archbishop [[Desmond Tutu]] * 1989 [[Eileen Egan]] * 1990 [[Mairead Corrigan|Mairead Corrigan Maguire]] * 1991 [[María Julia Hernández]] * 1992 [[Cesar Chavez]] * 1993 Father [[Daniel Berrigan]] * 1995 [[Jim Wallis]] * 1996 Bishop [[Samuel Ruiz García]] * 1997 [[Jim Douglass]] and [[Shelley Douglass]] * 1998 Sister [[Helen Prejean]], [[Congregation of the Sisters of Saint Joseph|CSJ]] * 1999 [[Adolfo Pérez Esquivel]] * 2000 Monsignor [[George G. Higgins]] * 2001 [[Lech Wałęsa]] * 2002 Sisters [[Gwen Hennessey]] and [[Dorothy Hennessey]], [[Franciscan|OSF]] * 2004 [[Minister (Christianity)|Rev.]] [[Arthur Simon]] * 2005 [[Donald Mosley]] * 2007 Bishop [[Salim Ghazal]] <ref name=DD/> * 2008 Monsignor [[Marvin Mottet]] * 2009 [[Hildegard Goss-Mayr]] * 2010 Father [[John Dear]]<ref name=DD/> * 2011 Bishop [[Álvaro Leonel Ramazzini Imeri]] * 2012 [[Kim Bobo]] * 2013 [[Jean Vanier]] * 2014 Sister [[Simone Campbell]], [[Sisters of Social Service|S.S.S.]] * 2015 [[Thích Nhất Hạnh]] <ref name="TNH">{{cite web |title=Thich Nhat Hanh named Pacem in Terris winner |url=https://www.catholicmessenger.net/2015/10/thich-nhat-hanh-named-pacem-in-terris-winner/ | newspaper=The Catholic Messenger (Davenport, IA)| accessdate=October 27, 2015}}</ref> * 2016 [[Gustavo Gutiérrez]] * 2017 [[Widad Akrawi|Dr. Widad Akreyi]] {{colend}}
